TheDream.US is already one of the nation‚Äôs larger college and career success programs, ‚Äúhaving provided more than 10,000 college scholarships to Dreamers attending 80+ partner colleges in 20+ states and Washington, D.C,‚Äù declares TheDream.US website. ‚ÄúWe believe everyone, regardless of where they were born, should have equitable access to a college education, a meaningful career, and opportunities to contribute to the communities they call home,‚Äù the message continues. There are roughly 2 million ‚ÄúDreamers‚Äù in the country, and an estimated 98,000 undocumented students, ages 15 to 19, graduate from a U.S. high school every year. However, only 5-to-10% enroll in college, states TheDream.US website. These students are at a great disadvantage when pursuing higher education: They typically receive no federal aid for college and often have limited access to state aid, with the added detriment of having to pay out-of-state tuition to attend in a state where help might be available. Being unable to officially call America ‚Äúhome‚Äù clearly makes it difficult to educate one-self beyond a standard high school diploma. The Opportunity Scholarship Award will cover eligible tuition, fees, on-campus housing, and meals for eligible students at one of the partner colleges, up to a maximum of $80,000 for pursuit of a bachelor‚Äôs degree. The award follows students through the completion of a bachelor‚Äôs degree and can be renewed each year. Updated: June 1, 2024 @ 11:55 pm Jason Moos is the director for the Columbia County Business Resource & Small Business Development Center. As the Small Business Development Director for Columbia County, I‚Äôm passionate about the vitality and growth of our local business ecosystem. The heartbeat of our community lies within the small businesses that line our streets, define our neighborhoods, and shape our unique identity. The essence of Columbia County thrives in these organizations, showcasing the craftsmanship, culture, and character that sets us apart. This holiday season, Keep it Local Columbia County‚Äôs Wonderland campaign is in full swing. A fun, and interactive rally call to our community to choose local businesses for our festive needs. The initiative highlights the unparalleled value that small businesses bring to our lives and emphasizes the pivotal role they play in our economic landscape, when we spend dollars locally. Last year‚Äôs efforts generated over $559,600 in local spending! There‚Äôs an intrinsic charm in shopping locally that transcends mere transactions. It‚Äôs about forging connections, fostering relationships, and investing in the prosperity of our neighbors. When you buy from a local artisan or a family-owned store, you‚Äôre not just acquiring a product; you‚Äôre supporting a dream, a livelihood, and a legacy. Your purchase resonates deeply, echoing in the success stories of entrepreneurs striving to make a difference in our community. The impact of shopping locally extends far beyond economic contributions. It bolsters community ties, cultivates a sense of belonging, and fortifies the very fabric of our society. These businesses sponsor Little League teams, participate in local events, and contribute to charitable causes, infusing our community with a sense of solidarity and unity. However, in a world of convenience and global markets, the allure of big-box stores and online giants can be enticing. Yet, the true essence of Columbia County lies in the nooks and crannies of our local shops, where each purchase is an investment in our collective future. The Keep it Local for the Holidays Wonderland campaign isn‚Äôt just about encouraging shopping habits; it‚Äôs about celebrating the essence of our community. It‚Äôs a reminder that every dollar spent locally reverberates, creating a ripple effect that sustains and strengthens our home. By choosing to shop locally this holiday season, you‚Äôre not just buying gifts; you‚Äôre investing in the backbone of Columbia County. Whether it‚Äôs a handcrafted ornament from a local artisan or a unique find from a boutique store, every purchase carries the spirit of our community. Let‚Äôs join hands this holiday season and amplify the heartbeat of Columbia County by keeping it local. Together, let‚Äôs make a difference, one purchase at a time, and foster a thriving, vibrant community that we are all proud to call home. Jason Moon is the Director of the Columbia County Small Business Development Center. You can reach the SBDC at 503-410-1506 or Columbia-county@oregonsbdc.org. Log In 1. Be Civil. Updated: June 2, 2024 @ 12:08 am As an outspoken leader for protecting communities from extreme wildfire and smoke events, Oregon‚Äôs U.S. Senator Jeff Merkley, Chairman of the Appropriations Subcommittee on the Interior, Environment, and Related Agencies, issued a statement following the Biden Administration‚Äôs announcement that it will issue a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) to strengthen federal coordination to protect communities from wildfire and smoke impacts: ‚ÄúAll Americans deserve clean air and water, healthy forests and ecosystems, and infrastructure that they can depend on. When catastrophic blazes take over and wildfire smoke blankets our communities, it‚Äôs dangerous for public health and hinders everyday life for those under the hazardous plumes of dark smoke emitted by these events. ‚ÄúAt a time when wildfires are an ever-growing threat in Oregon and across the West, it‚Äôs more critical than ever that the federal government invests in programs and solutions to help prevent and respond to dangerous megafires and smoke events. ‚ÄúAt my town halls in each of Oregon‚Äôs 36 counties this year, I heard firsthand from folks about what matters most to them, specifically the need to take on wildfire, smoke, and heat threats. As Chair of the Senate Interior Subcommittee on Appropriations, I have made it one of my top priorities to help address these concerns. It‚Äôs crucial that we make sure communities have access to all of the resources they need to not only battle blazes, but also protect themselves from the dangerous smoke and heat that has unfortunately become expected during these increasingly hot summer months. ‚ÄúI look forward to staying up to date with conversations and this MOU and seeing how these federal partnerships will play a key role in strengthening Oregon, and our country, for generations to come.‚Äù Merkley has spent years advocating for federal resources, solutions, and investments to combat increasingly extreme wildfire seasons and catastrophic smoke events that blanket the west. In Fiscal Year 2022, as Chairman of the Interior Environment Appropriations Committee, Merkley created this new program that funded wildfire smoke mitigation at $4 million. In Fiscal Year 2024, it‚Äôs currently marked in the Senate bill at $9 million. The EPA‚Äôs MOU is an outgrowth of the program and in line with Merkley‚Äôs Smoke and Heat Ready Communities Act bill and will be used to help coordinate between the different federal agencies. Merkley is also the author and lead sponsor of the Wildfire Smoke Emergency Declaration Act, which would allow the president to declare a ‚Äúsmoke emergency‚Äù and unleash federal assistance when wildfire smoke creates intense, hazardous air quality conditions. This MOU will be in partnership with Department of Interior (DOI), Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA), and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). Katie Walker takes command of the Gorge Composite at a Change of Command ceremony. THE GORGE ‚Äî This fall, the leadership of the Gorge Composite Squadron changed hands. On Sept. 19, Capt. Mo Donahue Revier stepped down after leading the squadron since June 2020, and 1st Lt. Katie Walker took command of the Gorge Composite. Then, on Oct. 3, C/Lt. Col. Isaac Walker, after more than two years of leadership, passed command of the cadets to C/2nd Lt. Zachary Luhan. Both Change of Command ceremonies took place at the Hood River Airport, where the squadron regularly meets on Tuesdays at 6:30 p.m. C/2nd Lt. Zachary Luhan and C/Lt. Col. Isaac Walker; Luhan is now in command of cadets. Katie Walker has been a member of the Civil Air Patrol since May 2019. She has served in several leadership roles, but her experience as the deputy commander of cadets has prepared her for this new leadership position. She currently resides in North Bonneville. Luhan joined the Civil Air Patrol in February 2020 and demonstrated commitment by his active participation throughout COVID and virtual meetings. Upon returning to in-person meetings, Luhan was promoted rapidly, held a variety of leadership positions and was well prepared to be the cadet commander, the highest ranking cadet in the Squadron. Luhan attended Mosier Community School and is currently a 10th grade student at Hood River Valley High School. Isaac Walker joined the Civil Air Patrol in February 2019. He has held every leadership position in Gorge Composite Squadron as well in Oregon. As a member of the Civil Air Patrol, he has represented Oregon in Washington, DC, volunteered at the AirVenture in Wisconsin as a Blue Beret, and earned his private pilot‚Äôs license. He plans to continue his education in the field of aviation at Walla Walla University. Donahue Revier was one of the founding members of the Gorge Composite Squadron in the fall 2017. Under her leadership, the Squadron was recognized as a Squadron of Merit in 2022, and earned the Quality Cadet Unit Award in 2021, 2022 and 2023. Cadets excelled within the Gorge Composite Squadron and participated in Civil Air Patrol opportunities throughout Oregon and the United States. The ceremony is a symbol of trust and respect. A flag is passed from the resigning commander to the leadership. This signifies the commander passing back the responsibility they were given. Leadership then passes the flag to the new commander, signifying the acceptance of the new responsibility. The hand-off also represents the trust between the two. The ceremony is then concluded, and the flag is returned to its stand. The Gorge Composite Squadron looks forward to its new leadership and celebrates the success of the former commanders. Founded in 1941 and established as the official civilian auxiliary of the U.S. Air Force seven years later, Civil Air Patrol is chartered by Congress as a nonprofit organization for the purposes of youth development, aerospace education, and to promote general aviation. In an auxiliary role as a Total Force partner of the Air Force, CAP operates the world‚Äôs largest fleet of single-engine aircraft for search and rescue, disaster relief, training, and education.
